    <h3>Accountability</h3>

    <p class="teaser">
      It was very recent that a U.S. President, his Secretary of State, and Congressional
      <em>leaders</em> lied Americans and Citizens throughout the world into a costly and
      needless war based on manipulation of largely fabricated intelligence. The Syria script
      smells a lot like an adaptation of the Iraq script, and, not surprisingly, involves many
      of the same actors.
    </p>

    <p class="teaser">
      The question avoided by the players and media lapdogs alike is the most obvious one:
      If the evil we are trying to remove from power remains in power, does that constitute a credible
      threat to the United States? The answer to that for Syria is exactly the same as it was for
      Libya and Iraq--and is and will be for Iran: No. There is no threat, immediate or otherwise.
      Therefore, <strong>NO</strong> is the only vote acceptable regarding whether to authorize
    military intervention in Syria.
      <a href="#" class="btn btn-xs more">More&nbsp;&gt;&gt;</a>
    </p>

    <p class="detail">
      The humanitarian argument is simply not credible coming from those who have killed, and continue
      to kill, innocents on a daily basis, dismissing them as collateral damage in a nebulous and
      astronomically expensive war on terror. Comparing the situations involving Bashar al-Assad
      and the Syrian civil war to Adolf Hitler and Nazi Germany is an insult to the intelligence
      of any thinking individual and an affront to Citizens everywhere.
    </p>

    <p class="detail">
      The impending decision that Congress has before it, is whether or not to go to war.
      You can call it what you like: surgical strike, limited engagement, no boots on
      the ground, whatever; let there be no doubt, striking Syria with missiles when
      they have not attacked us or our allies, <strong>is</strong> an act of war, and
    an act Syria would be fully justified in defending itself against. What then?
    Retaliation? This could escalate very easily.
    </p>

    <p class="detail">
      This vote by Congress could very well be the spark that sets off World War III or, equally
      possible, an economic meltdown. Both of these outcomes are very real possibilities; the risk
      vs reward proposition regarding intervening in Syria is heavily in favor if it ending badly.
      <em>Therefore</em> we regard any members of congress who votes in favor of intervention in
      Syria as either foolhardy, or is placing other interests in front of the Citizens they serve.
      Both are sufficient cause for Citizens to use whatever legal means necessary to
      prevent their reelection where they would only do more mischief.
    </p>

    <p class="detail">
      We are, and will be keeping track of each vote for Syrian intervention made by
      congress so Citizens can hold them accountable for their mistake.
